ninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1573–1639":"1573–1639","1575–1668":"1575–1668","1593–1650":"1593–1650","1554–1590":"1554–1590","1551–1594":"1551–1594","1668":"1668","1554":"1554","21 Nov 1570":"21 November 1570","1575":"1575","September 22, 1590":"22 September 1590","1573":"1573","1551":"1551","1650":"1650","1594":"1594","1593":"1593","1639":"1639","1590":"1590","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Kreyfort, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Cleburne Hall, Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Saint Mary the Virgin's Church, Blundeston, East Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary The Virgin's Church, Blundeston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Claiborne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Clabburn</b>, possibly a variant of   Cliburn  , but the latter is a northwest English name whereas <b>Clabburn</b> is found mostly in Norfolk and the South East, so it is more probably from a lost place in that part of England, perhaps named with Old English <i>clǣg</i> ‘clay’ + <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’.","History: William Claiborne (<i>c.</i> 1600–77) was a founding colonist in VA. His descendant, William Charles Claiborne (1775–1817) was the first governor of LA."],"variants":[{"name":"Claborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Claiborne  ."]},{"name":"Clayborne","meanings":["English: variant of   Claiborne  ."]},{"name":"Clayborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Claiborne  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Cliburn","meanings":["English (Middlesex): habitational name from Cliburn (Westmorland), named from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope, bank’ + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’. Alternatively, from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Clibern</i>, of uncertain origin."]},{"name":"Clayburn","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): variant of   Claiborne  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas G. Claiborne was born in 1573, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Nathaniel Claiborne, was 19 and his mother, Grace Bellingham, was 22. He married Sarah Elizabeth Fenne in 1593, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1639, in his hometown, at the age of 66, and was buried in St Mary The Virgin's Church, Blundeston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1573–1639":"1573–1639","1575–1668":"1575–1668","1593–1650":"1593–1650","1554–1590":"1554–1590","1551–1594":"1551–1594","1668":"1668","1554":"1554","21 Nov 1570":"21. november 1570","1575":"1575","September 22, 1590":"22. september 1590","1573":"1573","1551":"1551","1650":"1650","1594":"1594","1593":"1593","1639":"1639","1590":"1590","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kreyfort, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cleburne Hall, Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Mary the Virgin's Church, Blundeston, East Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary The Virgin's Church, Blundeston, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"15